@tagheuer is back on the grid with two new Formula 1 Solargraph watches that blend race-ready performance with bold design. The standout 38mm pastel series refreshes classic F1 design codes in soft beige, pink, blue, lavender, and green shades, all powered by Solargraph tech that needs just minutes of sunlight to keep ticking for months.⁠
⁠
Joining it is the Formula 1 Solargraph Indy 500, a tribute to the iconic race featuring Indy 500 branding, a brick-pattern dial inspired by the Speedway’s Yard of Bricks, and a sleek black-and-steel finish. Together, both releases continue the Formula 1 collection’s legacy of mixing accessible innovation with unmistakable motorsport style.

@bentotecamilano expands its world beyond the table with a range of graphic-heavy T-shirts that feel like an extension of the dining experience itself. ⁠
⁠
Known as one of Milan’s standout Japanese restaurants, the project translates its atmosphere, details, and visual language into wearable form. It’s merch, but treated with the same care and precision as the food. Swipe for a closer look.

@JacobAndCo. unveils the Godfather II, a $440,000 musical timepiece that brings cinema to the wrist.
Drawing inspiration from one of film’s most iconic sagas, the watch integrates two legendary compositions — The Godfather’s Waltz and The Godfather Love Theme — played through an intricate, built-in music box.
Encased in a sculpted Art Deco-inspired design, the piece combines horological artistry with cinematic storytelling. A flying tourbillon, dual power reserves, and a newly engineered movement elevate both its technical and aesthetic appeal, while the dial features a finely detailed portrait of Don Corleone alongside subtle references to the film’s legacy.
Limited to just 74 pieces, in tribute to the 1974 release of The Godfather Part II, the timepiece stands as a rare collector’s creation, where music, craftsmanship, and heritage converge.
